{{Infobox book | name = American Grown | image = American Grown (Michelle Obama book).jpg | caption = | author = [[Michelle Obama]] | illustrator = | cover_artist = | country = | language = | series = | subject = [[White House Vegetable Garden]] | genre = Non-fiction | publisher = [[Crown Publishing Group|Crown]] | pub_date = May 29, 2012 | media_type = Hardcover | pages = 272 pp. | isbn = 978-0-307-95602-6 | oclc = | dewey = | congress = | preceded_by = | followed_by = }}
'''''American Grown: The Story of the White House Kitchen Garden and Gardens Across America''''' is a book by [[First Lady of the United States]] [[Michelle Obama]] published in 2012. The book promotes healthy eating and documents the [[White House Kitchen Garden]] through the seasons. The garden, planted in 2009 on the White House's [[South Lawn (White House)|South Lawn]], was instrumental in the First Lady's [[Let's Move!]] initiative to end childhood obesity.<ref>{{cite news|last=Burros|first=Marian|title=Michelle Obama Reveals How Her White House Garden Grows|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2012/05/29/us/politics/michelle-obama-writes-american-grown.html|newspaper=The New York Times|date=May 29, 2012}}</ref> Journalist Lyric Winik assisted Obama in the writing of ''American Grown'' and proceeds will be donated to the [[National Park Foundation]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Michelle Obama on New Book, 'American Grown'|url=http://abcnews.go.com/GMA/video/michelle-obama-book-american-grown-16448732|publisher=ABC News|date=May 29, 2012}}</ref>
''American Grown'' is divided into four sections (one for each season) and includes color photographs of vegetables, as well as recipes,<ref>{{cite web|title=White House's Summer Chopped Salad|url=http://abcnews.go.com/GMA/recipe/american-grown-summer-chopped-salad-white-house-kitchen-16447131|publisher=ABC News|accessdate=June 3, 2012}}</ref> instructions for making a [[compost]] bin, and stories about [[community gardening in the United States|community gardens in the United States]].<ref name="Benac">{{cite news|last=Benac|first=Nancy|title=Michelle Obama's Book On Growing Seeds and Healthy Kids|url=http://www.theledger.com/article/20120601/NEWS/120609973|newspaper=The Ledger|date=June 1, 2012|agency=Associated Press}}</ref> The book delves into the history of gardens at the White House, including First Lady [[Eleanor Roosevelt]]'s [[victory garden]] and [[Thomas Jefferson]]'s attempts to grow a four-foot-long cucumber.<ref name="Benac"/> Obama describes how the Kitchen Garden's Jefferson beds include a quote from the former President that is also a guiding principle for the garden: "the failure of one thing repaired by the success of another; and instead of one harvest, a continued one throughout the year."<ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=ePis-f38ds4C&lpg=PP1&dq=american%20grown%20obama&pg=PA26#v=onepage&q=american%20grown%20obama&f=false ''American Grown'', p. 26]</ref>
''American Grown'' blends the First Lady's personal gardening experiences with stories from the White House Kitchen Garden. Obama writes about the time in her life when she had "no idea that tomatoes didn’t come in green plastic trays, covered by cellophane, and that they could be any color other than pale red."<ref>{{cite news|title=Table Talk: Michelle Obama And The White House Garden|url=http://www.huffingtonpost.com/2012/06/01/table-talk-michelle-obama-american-grown_n_1563394.html|newspaper=Huffington Post|date=June 1, 2012}}</ref> The portion of the book devoted to the White House [[beehive]] describes how an apple tree in the Children's Garden produced fruit for the first time in 25 years after the introduction of bees.<ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=ePis-f38ds4C&lpg=PP1&dq=american%20grown%20obama&pg=PA45#v=onepage&q&f=false ''American Grown'', p. 45]</ref> Through her research for the book, Obama discovered that her maternal grandmother tended a community victory garden in Chicago.<ref>{{cite news|title=The First Lady Cultivates 'American Grown' Gardening|url=https://www.npr.org/2012/05/29/153705721/the-first-lady-cultivates-american-grown-gardening|newspaper=NPR|date=May 29, 2012}}</ref>
A review in ''[[The New York Times]]'' referred to Obama's book "charming and thought-provoking", writer Dominique Browning also stating that the garden serves as a good example to call the country's attention to the connection between food quality and health.<ref>{{cite news|last=Browning|first=Dominique|title=Gardening: Michelle Obama’s ‘American Grown,’ and More|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2012/06/03/books/review/michelle-obamas-american-grown-and-more.html?_r=1|newspaper=The New York Times|date=June 1, 2012}}</ref>
