{{Use dmy dates|date=May 2017}} {{Use British English|date=May 2017}} {{Infobox Bus transit |name = London Electrobus Company |logo = |logo_size = |image = |image_size = |image_caption = |company_slogan = |parent = |Company number = |founded = April 1906 |headquarters = 1 Earl Street, Westminster |locale = |service_area = London |service_type = Bus services |destinations = |fleet = |Managing Director = |website = }} The '''London Electrobus Company''', was a [[bus]] operator that ran a fleet of [[electric bus]]es in [[London]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.gracesguide.co.uk/London_Electrobus_Co|title=London Electrobus Co - Graces Guide|website=www.gracesguide.co.uk|language=en|access-date=2017-11-11}}</ref> The electrobus was the first practical battery-electric bus and a forerunner of the electric buses that are experiencing a major resurgence in the 21st century.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=|first=|date=9 September 2017|title=All Aboard|url=https://www.newscientist.com/|journal=New Scientist|volume=|pages= 35–37|via=}}</ref>
The company, which was first registered in April 1906, started running a service of electrobuses between London's Victoria Station and Liverpool Street on 15 July 1907.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=|first=|date=8 September 2007|title=What is this that roareth thus|url=https://www.economist.com/|journal=The Economist Technology Quarterly|volume=|pages=9|via=}}</ref> The clean and quiet electrobuses were popular with the travelling public.<ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=a5CS6IcW0FEC&pg=PA38&lpg=PA38&dq=%22london+electrobus+company%22&source=bl&ots=G80yxeApoR&sig=ROkkBAlITZD1kyvqcqBaEblNWVg&hl=en&ei=PCJITMqZNYyTjAfFwuzUDg&sa=X&oi=book_result&ct=result&resnum=2&ved=0CBkQ6AEwATgK#v=onepage&q=%22london%20electrobus%20company%22&f=false Google Books - New Scientist, 17 July 1986]</ref> The company introduced a number of innovations and it was the first [[double-decker bus]] operator to experiment with a roof on the upper deck.<ref name=":0">[http://www.ianvisits.co.uk/blog/2014/01/09/the-fraud-that-killed-off-londons-first-electric-buses/ The Fraud that Killed Off London’s First Electric Buses] - Ian Mansfield, 9 January 2014 </ref> At the peak of its success in late 1908 the company had 20 or so buses in operation<ref>{{Cite book|title=Electric Vehicles|last=Georgano|first=Nick|publisher=Shire Publications|year=1996|isbn=9780747803164|location=|pages=20–21}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=|first=|date=31 December 1908|title=Our Fortnightly Census|url=http://archive.commercialmotor.com/page/31st-december-1908/6|journal=Commercial Motor|volume=|pages= 336|via=}}</ref> and it started to run a second bus route from Victoria to Kilburn.
However, the London Electrobus Company was beset by financial chicanery throughout its short existence.<ref name=":0" /> By 3 January 1910 the electrobus service had ceased and the company went into liquidation amid accusations of fraud.<ref name=":1">{{Cite book|title=A Most Deliberate Swindle|last=Hamer|first=Mick|publisher=RedDoor|year=2017|isbn=9781910453421|location=London|pages=171, 197}}</ref> Eight of the electrobuses were sold to the Brighton, Hove and Preston United company.<ref>{{Cite book|title=British Battery Electric Buses|last=Kaye|first=David|publisher=The Oakwood Press|year=1976|isbn=|location=|pages=8}}</ref> The rest of the London electrobuses were broken up for spares. The Brighton bus company was taken over by [[Thomas Tilling]] in 1916<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://history.buses.co.uk/history/cohistory/welcome.htm|title=Brighton and Hove Buses company history|last=|first=|date=|website=|archive-url=|archive-date=|dead-url=|access-date=}}</ref> and the last electrobus in Brighton ran in April 1917. Tilling said that a lack of spare parts had forced it to stop running electrobuses.<ref name=":1" />
