[[File:Reta Beebe.gif|right|frame|Reta Beebe in 1995]] '''Reta F. Beebe''' (born October 10, 1936 in Baca County Colorado) is an [[United States|American]] [[astronomer]], [[author]], and [[popularizer of science|popularizer]] of [[astronomy]]. She is an expert on the planets [[Jupiter]] and [[Saturn]], and the author of ''Jupiter: The Giant Planet''.<ref>Beebe, Reta (1994) ''Jupiter: The Giant Planet'' Smithsonian Institution Press, Washington, D.C., {{ISBN|1-56098-417-1}}; second edition 1997, {{ISBN|1-56098-731-6}}</ref> She is a [[professor emeritus]] in the Astronomy Department at [[New Mexico State University]] and 2010 winner of the [[NASA]] Exceptional Public Service medal.<ref name="abq">Associated Press (15 September 2010) [http://www.abqjournal.com/news/state/apnasamedal09-15-10.htm "NASA Medal Awarded to NMSU Astronomer"] ''Alubuquerque Journal''</ref><ref>Associated Press (15 September 2010) [http://www.lcsun-news.com/las_cruces-news/ci_16078874 "NASA medal awarded to NMSU astronomer" ''Las Cruces Sun-News'' ]</ref>
Beebe spent many years helping to plan and manage NASA missions, including the [[Voyager program]] missions to the giant planets. Her specific research interest was the atmospheres of Jupiter, Saturn, [[Uranus]], and [[Neptune]]. She designed experiments to the study and measure the clouds and winds of the giant planets.<ref>Staff (13 May 2002) [http://www1.ucsc.edu/currents/01-02/05-13/morenews.html#Astronomer "Astronomer Reta Beebe to give community talk May 15"] ''University of California Santa Cruz Currents''</ref> She worked interpreting the [[Galileo (spacecraft)|Galileo]] and [[Cassini–Huygens|Cassini]] data and used the [[Hubble Space Telescope]] to obtain additional atmospheric data on Jupiter and Saturn. She was a member of the [[Comet Shoemaker-Levy 9|Shoemaker/Levy]] team at the [[Space Telescope Science Institute]] in 1994 when the comet struck Jupiter. Formerly, she chaired the Committee for Planetary and Lunar Exploration (COMPLEX), which is the principal space committee of the [[United States National Research Council]].<ref name="DPS-Award">[http://dps.aas.org/prizes/2003 "Year 2003 DPS Prize Recipients"]</ref> More recently she was involved with organizing the data about the giant planets in NASA's [[Planetary Data System]]. She is in charge of the Atmospheres Discipline Node of that program.<ref>[http://pds-atmospheres.nmsu.edu/ "Welcome to the PDS Atmospheres Node"] New Mexico State University</ref> Her planetary data archiving skills have also been employed by the [[European Space Agency]].<ref name="abq" /> She serves on the steering committee of the [[International Planetary Data Alliance]].<ref name="abq" />
==Awards== * 1989 Westhafer Award for Excellence in Teaching, Research, or Creative Activity from New Mexico State University<ref name="NMSU-news">[http://newscenter.nmsu.edu/news/article/?action=show&id=5390 "NMSU astronomer receives top public service medal from NASA"] New Mexico State University News Center</ref> * 1998 Dennis W. Darnall Faculty Achievement Award from New Mexico State University<ref name="NMSU-news" /> * 2003 [[Masursky Award|Harold Masursky Award]] from the Division for Planetary Sciences of the [[American Astronomical Society]]<ref name="DPS-Award" /> * 2010 NASA Exceptional Public Service medal<ref name="abq" />
